Stack and heap are two distinct areas of RAM, and provide different characteristic.

Stack Memory (Local & Fast)
Purpose: Stores local variables, function parameters, and return addresses.
Access: Very fast access, cache-friendly.
Lifespan: Data is created when a function is called and automatically deleted when it returns. ( This is about stack frame )
Organization: Strict LIFO structure (like a pile of books).

Heap Memory (Dynamic & Flexible) 
Purpose: Stores objects, arrays, and data that require a longer lifespan or dynamic sizing (e.g., new objects in Java/C++).
Access: Slower than the stack.
Lifespan: Data exists until it is explicitly freed (like free in C) or removed by a garbage collector.
Organization: No strict order, dispersed throughout memory (can lead to fragmentation).

Stack frame

When call a function, it actualy create a new stack frame ( shadow space, etc and it is not create by a call, you know, as explain in Last file.) . And here, we gonna dive deeper into this !
There are two register, RSP ( had been talked about in first file ), and RBP (register base pointer )

Feature 	        RSP (Stack Pointer)                        	RBP (Base Pointer)
Primary Role	    Tracks the active top of the stack.	        Defines a fixed base for the current frame.
Movement	        Changes frequently (PUSH/POP/CALL).	        Usually stays fixed during function execution.
Usage	            Required for hardware stack operations.	    Optional (often omitted for optimization).
Addressing	      [rsp + offset] (offsets can change).	      [rbp - offset] (offsets remain constant).

The frame layout

                Caller Frame
                Shadow space
                Return address (8 bit)
                Saved RBP
                Local Variables
                Saved registers
                RSP ( current top )

Memory Address	Data Item	Who is Responsible?	Purpose
Higher	Arg 5, 6, ...	Caller	Arguments that didn't fit in registers.
Shadow Space (32 bytes)	Caller	Space for the callee to save RCX, RDX, R8, R9.
Return Address (8 bytes)	call Instruction	Where the CPU goes after ret.
Saved RBP (8 bytes)	Callee (Prologue)	Preserves the caller's frame pointer (optional).
Local Variables	Callee (Prologue)	Storage for internal function data.
Saved Registers	Callee (Prologue)	Preserves non-volatile registers like RBX, RSI.
Lower	(Current RSP)	—	The "top" of the stack.



Remind :16-Byte Alignment: On x64, the stack pointer (RSP) must be 16-byte aligned before making a CALL to another function. 
Since the CALL instruction pushes an 8-byte return address, the stack is usually 8-byte misaligned when a function begins its execution. 

But the saved RBP is 8 bit, so it is exactly 16 bit aligned
